Definition 9.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a small $\mathcal{V}$-category. A full replete subcategory $\mathcal{W}\subseteq[\mathcal{C}^{\mathrm{op}},\mathcal{V}]$ is called self-cocomplete if (sc-1) $\mathcal{W}$ contains all the representable functors $\mathcal{C}(\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,,C)$, $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and (sc-2) $\mathcal{W}$ is closed under $\mathcal{W}$-weighted colimits (of $\mathcal{V}$-functors $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{W}$).
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a symmetric monoidal closed category with small limits and colimits. A skew monoidal $\mathcal{V}$-actegory $\langle\mathcal{M}_{0},\odot,a,l,\ast,\Gamma,\Gamma^{\prime},R,\gamma,\eta,\varepsilon\rangle$ is called a skew monoidal tensored $\mathcal{V}$-category or, what is the same, a skew monoidal hommed $\mathcal{V}$-actegory if the following condition holds: (i) For each object $M$ of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ the functor $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\odot M:\mathcal{V}\to\mathcal{M}_{0}$ has a right adjoint $\mathcal{M}(M,\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,)$. A skew monoidal tensored $\mathcal{V}$-category is called r2-exact if: (ii) The category $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ has reflexive coequalizers. (iii) For each object $V$ of $\mathcal{V}$ the functor $V\odot\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{M}_{0}\to\mathcal{M}_{0}$ preserves reflexive coequalizers. (iv) For each object $M$ of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ the functor $M\ast\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{M}_{0}\to\mathcal{M}_{0}$ is strong, i.e., $\Gamma^{\prime}$ is an isomorphism. (v) For each object $M$ of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ the functor $M\ast\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{M}_{0}\to\mathcal{M}_{0}$ preserves reflexive coequalizers. Similarly, we define r1-exactness by requiring, instead of (iv) and (v), invertibility of $\Gamma$ and preservation of reflexive coequalizers by the functors $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\ast M$. If $\mathcal{M}$ is both r1-exact and r2-exact then it is called r-exact.
Definition 9.6. A small set $\{M_{i}\,|\,i\in\mathcal{I}\}$ of objects of a $\mathcal{V}$-category is called well-generating if the inclusion $J:\mathcal{C}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{M}$ of the full subcategory generated by the $\{M_{i}\}$ is well-behaved.
Definition 2.4. A morphism $\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ of left $\mathcal{V}$-actegories consists of • a functor $F:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ • and a natural transformation $F_{V,M}:V\odot FM\to F(V\odot M)$, called the strength, subject to the coherence conditions $\displaystyle F_{V\odot W,M}\,\circ\,a_{V,W,FM}$ $\displaystyle=Fa_{V,W,M}\,\circ\,F_{V,W\odot M}\,\circ\,(V\odot F_{V,M})$ $\displaystyle F_{I,M}\,\circ\,l_{FM}$ $\displaystyle=Fl_{M}\,.$ The morphism $F$ is called strong when its strength is an isomorphism and strict when its strength is the identity.
Definition 2.1. A left actegory over $\mathcal{V}$ consists of • a category $\mathcal{M}$, • a functor $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\odot\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{V}\times\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M}$ • and natural isomorphisms $\displaystyle a_{U,V,M}:U\odot(V\odot M)$ $\displaystyle\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}(U\odot V)\odot M$ $\displaystyle l_{M}:M$ $\displaystyle\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}I\odot M$ satisfying one pentagon and two triangle conditions $\displaystyle(a_{U,V,W}\odot M)\,\circ\,a_{U,V\odot W,M}\,\circ\,(U\odot a_{V,% W,M})$ $\displaystyle=a_{U\odot V,W,M}\,\circ\,a_{U,V,W\odot M}$ $\displaystyle a_{I,V,M}\,\circ\,l_{V\odot M}$ $\displaystyle=l_{V}\odot M$ $\displaystyle(r_{V}\odot M)\,\circ\,a_{V,I,M}\,\circ\,(V\odot l_{M})$ $\displaystyle=V\odot M\,.$
Definition 2.5. Let $F,G:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ be morphisms of left $\mathcal{V}$-actegories. A transformation $F\to G$ of actegory morphisms is nothing but a natural transformation $\nu:F\to G$ satisfying $\nu_{V\odot M}\,\circ\,F_{V,M}\ =\ G_{V,M}\,\circ\,(V\odot\nu_{M})\,.$
Definition 3.1. A skew monoidal $\mathcal{V}$-actegory consists of • a $\mathcal{V}$-actegory $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ with action $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\odot\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{V}\times\mathcal{M}_{0}\to% \mathcal{M}_{0}$ and with coherence morphisms $\displaystyle a_{U,V,M}:U\odot(V\odot M)$ $\displaystyle\to(U\odot V)\odot M$ $\displaystyle l_{M}:M$ $\displaystyle\to I\odot M$ • a 2-variable morphism $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\ast\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{M}_{0}\times\mathcal{M}_{0}\to% \mathcal{M}_{0}$ of $\mathcal{V}$-actegories, the skew tensor, with strengths $\displaystyle\Gamma_{V,M,N}$ $\displaystyle:V\odot(M\ast N)\to(V\odot M)\ast N$ $\displaystyle\Gamma^{\prime}_{V,M,N}$ $\displaystyle:V\odot(M\ast N)\to M\ast(V\odot N)\,,$ • an object $R$ of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$, called the skew unit, • and transformations of actegory morphisms $\displaystyle\gamma_{L,M,N}$ $\displaystyle:L\ast(M\ast N)\to(L\ast M)\ast N$ $\displaystyle\eta_{M}$ $\displaystyle:M\to R\ast M$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon_{M}$ $\displaystyle:M\ast R\to M\,.$ The transformations are required to satisfy the skew monoidality axioms $\displaystyle(\gamma_{K,L,M}\ast N)\,\circ\,\gamma_{K,L\ast M,N}\,\circ\,(K% \ast\gamma_{L,M,N})$ $\displaystyle=\gamma_{K\ast L,M,N}\,\circ\,\gamma_{K,L,M\ast N}$ $\displaystyle\gamma_{R,M,N}\,\circ\,\eta_{M\ast N}$ $\displaystyle=\eta_{M}\ast N$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon_{M\ast N}\,\circ\,\gamma_{M,N,R}$ $\displaystyle=M\ast\varepsilon_{N}$ $\displaystyle(\varepsilon_{M}\ast N)\,\circ\,\gamma_{M,R,N}\,\circ\,(M\ast\eta% _{N})$ $\displaystyle=M\ast N$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon_{R}\,\circ\,\eta_{R}$ $\displaystyle=R$
Definition 2.7. For left actegories ${}_{\mathcal{V}}\mathcal{M}$ and ${}_{\mathcal{W}}\mathcal{N}$ a morphism ${}_{\mathcal{V}}\mathcal{M}\to\,_{\mathcal{W}}\mathcal{N}$ is a pair ${}_{F}F^{\prime}$ consisting of a monoidal functor $F:\mathcal{V}\to\mathcal{W}$ and of a functor $F^{\prime}:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ equipped with strength $F^{\prime}_{V,M}:FV\odot F^{\prime}M\to F^{\prime}(V\odot M)$ subject to the coherence conditions $\displaystyle F^{\prime}_{V_{1}\odot V_{2},M}\,\circ\,(F_{V_{1},V_{2}}\odot F^% {\prime}M)\,\circ\,a_{FV_{1},FV_{2},F^{\prime}M}$ $\displaystyle=F^{\prime}a_{V_{1},V_{2},M}\,\circ\,F^{\prime}_{V_{1},V_{2}\odot M% }\,\circ\,(FV_{1}\odot F^{\prime}_{V_{2},M})$ $\displaystyle F^{\prime}_{I,M}\,\circ\,(F_{0}\odot F^{\prime}M)\,\circ\,l_{F^{% \prime}M}$ $\displaystyle=F^{\prime}l_{M}\,.$ For a parallel pair ${}_{F}F^{\prime}$, ${}_{G}G^{\prime}$ of actegory morphisms ${}_{\mathcal{V}}\mathcal{M}\to_{\mathcal{W}}\mathcal{N}$ a transformation ${}_{F}F^{\prime}\to\,_{G}G^{\prime}$ is a pair ${}_{\nu}\nu^{\prime}$ consisting of a monoidal natural transformation $\nu:F\to G$ and of a natural transformation $\nu^{\prime}:F^{\prime}\to G^{\prime}$ satisfying $\nu^{\prime}_{V\odot M}\,\circ\,F^{\prime}_{V,M}\ =\ G^{\prime}_{V,M}\,\circ\,% (\nu_{V}\odot\nu^{\prime}_{M})\,.$
Definition 2.6. For left $\mathcal{V}$-actegories $\mathcal{M}_{1}$,…,$\mathcal{M}_{n}$ and $\mathcal{N}$ an $n$-variable morphism $\mathcal{M}_{1}\times\dots\times\mathcal{M}_{n}\to\mathcal{N}$ of left $\mathcal{V}$-actegories is a functor $F:\mathcal{M}_{1}\times\dots\times\mathcal{M}_{n}\to\mathcal{N}$ such that (i) for each index $1\leq k\leq n$ there is a natural transformation $F^{(k)}_{V,\underline{M}}\ :\ V\odot F(\underline{M})\to F(V\underset{k}{\odot% }\underline{M}),$ where $V\underset{k}{\odot}\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,$ denotes the action of $V$ on the $k$-th argument, such that for each fixed $M_{i}$, $i\neq k$, the $F^{(k)}_{V,\underline{M}}$ is a strength for the $k$-th partial functor $F(M_{1},\dots,M_{k-1},\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,,M_{k+1},\dots,M_{n})\ :\ \mathcal{M}_{k% }\to\mathcal{N}\,;$ (ii) for each pair of indices $1\leq j<k\leq n$ the strengths $F^{(j)}$ and $F^{(k)}$ are compatible in the sense of $\displaystyle F^{(k)}_{V,U\underset{j}{\odot}\underline{M}}\,\circ\,(V\odot F^% {(j)}_{U,\underline{M}})$ $\displaystyle=F^{(j)}_{U,V\underset{k}{\odot}\underline{M}}\,\circ\,(U\odot F^% {(k)}_{V,\underline{M}})\,\circ$ $\displaystyle\,\circ\,a^{-1}_{U,V,F\underline{M}}\,\circ\,(s_{V,U}\odot F% \underline{M})\,\circ\,a_{V,U,F\underline{M}}$ where $s_{U,V}:U\odot V\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}V\odot U$ is the symmetry in $\mathcal{V}$. For a parallel pair of $n$-variable actegory morphisms $F,G:\mathcal{M}_{1}\times\dots\times\mathcal{M}_{n}\to\mathcal{N}$ a transformation $\nu:F\to G$ is a natural transformation that satisfies (12) in each variable.
Definition 2.2. A right skew actegory over a skew monoidal $\mathcal{V}$ consists of • a category $\mathcal{M}$, • a functor $\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,\odot\mbox{\,\rm\_}\,:\mathcal{M}\times\mathcal{V}\to\mathcal{M}$ • and natural transformations $\displaystyle a_{M,U,V}:M\odot(U\odot V)$ $\displaystyle\to(M\odot U)\odot V$ $\displaystyle r_{M}:M\odot I$ $\displaystyle\to M$ satisfying one pentagon and two triangle conditions $\displaystyle(a_{M,U,V}\odot W)\,\circ\,a_{M,U\odot V,W}\,\circ\,(M\odot a_{U,% V,W})$ $\displaystyle=a_{M\odot U,V,W}\,\circ\,a_{M,U,V\odot W}$ $\displaystyle(r_{M}\odot V)\,\circ\,a_{M,I,V}\,\circ\,(M\odot l_{V})$ $\displaystyle=M\odot V$ $\displaystyle r_{M\odot V}\,\circ\,a_{M,V,I}$ $\displaystyle=M\odot r_{V}\,.$
Definition 4.1. Given a unital $C^{\ast}$-subalgebra $\mathcal{N}\subset\mathcal{A}$ we define its dual as $\mathcal{N}^{\perp}:=\big{\{}\rho\in\operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}:\rho(n)=% n,\,n\in\mathcal{N}\big{\}}$ and $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{N}^{\perp}}(\rho,\sigma):=\operatorname{Hom}_{% \operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}}(\rho,\sigma)$ for every $\rho,\sigma\in\mathcal{N}^{\perp}$. In other words, $\mathcal{N}^{\perp}\subset\operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}$ is a full subcategory, i.e., specified by its objects only.
Definition 6.1. We call abstract point of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ an ordered pair of algebras $(\mathcal{N},\mathcal{N}^{c})$ where $\mathcal{N}\subset\mathcal{M}_{0}$ such that (i) $\mathcal{N}$ and $\mathcal{N}^{c}$ are injective type ${I\!I\!I}_{1}$ factors. (ii) $\mathcal{N}=\mathcal{N}^{cc}$ and $\mathcal{N}\vee\mathcal{N}^{c}=\mathcal{M}_{0}$. (iii) $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{N}}\simeq\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{N}^{c}}\simeq\mathcal{C}$ as UBTCs. (iv) $\text{\Large{$\varepsilon$}}_{\rho,\sigma}=\mathds{1}$ whenever $\rho\in\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{N}}$, $\sigma\in\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{N}^{c}}$. With abuse of notation we denote abstract points by $p:=(\mathcal{N},\mathcal{N}^{c})$, and call $\mathcal{N}$, $\mathcal{N}^{c}$ respectively the left, right relative complement of $p$ in $\mathcal{M}_{0}$.
Definition 2.1. A net of von Neumann algebras $\{\mathcal{A}\}=\{I\in\mathcal{I}\mapsto\mathcal{A}(I)\}$ realized on $\mathcal{H}$ is a local conformal net on the line if it fulfills: • Isotony: if $I,J\in\mathcal{I}$ and $I\subset J$ then $\mathcal{A}(I)\subset\mathcal{A}(J)$. • Locality: if $I,J\in\mathcal{I}$ and $I\cap J=\emptyset$ then $\mathcal{A}(I)$ and $\mathcal{A}(J)$ elementwise commute. • Möbius covariance: there is a strongly continuous unitary representation $U$ of the Möbius group $\mathsf{M\ddot{o}b}=PSL(2,\mathbb{R})=SL(2,\mathbb{R})/\{\pm\mathds{1}\}$ on $\mathcal{H}$, which acts covariantly on the net, i.e. $U(g)\mathcal{A}(I)U(g)^{*}=\mathcal{A}(gI)$ whenever $I\in\mathcal{I}$, $g\in\mathsf{M\ddot{o}b}$ and $gI\in\mathcal{I}$, we ask nothing otherwise. • Positivity of the (conformal) Hamiltonian: the generator $H$ of the rotations subgroup of $\mathsf{M\ddot{o}b}$ is positive. • Vacuum vector: there exists a Möbius invariant vector $\Omega\in\mathcal{H}$, unique up to scalar multiples, and cyclic for $\{\mathcal{A}(I)$, $U(g):I\in\mathcal{I},g\in\mathsf{M\ddot{o}b}\}$. A local conformal net on the line (in a vacuum sector) is then specified by a quadruple $(\{\mathcal{A}\},U,\Omega,\mathcal{H})$.
Definition 8.5. Let $\{\mathcal{A}\}$ be a completely rational conformal net on the line. Fix arbitrarily $I_{0}\in\mathcal{I}$ and let $\mathcal{M}_{0}=\mathcal{A}(I_{0})$, $\mathcal{C}=\operatorname{DHR}^{I_{0}}\{\mathcal{A}\}$. We call $\{\mathcal{A}\}$ a prime conformal net if the following conditions are satisfied. • $\mathcal{C}\simeq\operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}$ is a prime UMTC. • For every ordered pair $p=(\mathcal{N},\mathcal{N}^{c})$, $q=(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{M}^{c})$ of abstract points of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$, if $\mathcal{N}\vee\mathcal{M}^{c}$ is normal in $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ then $\mathcal{M}\subset\mathcal{N}$, in particular $\mathcal{N}\vee\mathcal{M}^{c}=\mathcal{M}_{0}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an abstract strict UMTC and $\mathcal{M}$ a von Neumann factor. A strict tensor replete embedding $G:\mathcal{C}\hookrightarrow\operatorname{End}(\mathcal{M})$ will be called a braided action of $\mathcal{C}$ on $\mathcal{M}$.
Definition 5.1. Let $\mathcal{C}\subset\operatorname{DHR}^{I_{0}}\{\mathcal{A}\}$ be a unital full inclusion of tensor categories, we define the relative commutant as $\mathcal{C}^{c}:=\big{\{}\rho\in\operatorname{DHR}^{I_{0}}\{\mathcal{A}\}:\rho% \,\sigma=\sigma\rho,\,\sigma\in\mathcal{C}\big{\}}$ where the equality sign means pointwise equality as endomorphisms of $\mathcal{A}(I_{0})$, or equivalently of $\mathcal{A}$. We define $\mathcal{C}^{c}\subset\operatorname{DHR}^{I_{0}}\{\mathcal{A}\}$ as a full subcategory, i.e., $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}^{c}}(\rho,\sigma):=\operatorname{Hom}_{% \operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}}(\rho,\sigma)$ for every $\rho,\sigma\in\mathcal{C}^{c}$.
Definition 9.3. Let $\{\mathcal{A}\}$ be a completely rational conformal net on the line. In the notation of Definition 6.1, two abstract points $p=(\mathcal{N},\mathcal{N}^{c})$, $q=(\mathcal{M},\mathcal{M}^{c})$ of $\mathcal{M}_{0}$ are called comparable if they fulfill the following • $\mathcal{U}_{\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{R}^{c}}\cap\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{S}^{c}}}(% \mathcal{R},\mathcal{S})={\mathcal{U}_{\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{R}^{c}}\cap% \mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{S}^{c}}}(\mathcal{R},\mathcal{S})}^{cc}$. • $\mathcal{R}\vee\mathcal{S}=(\mathcal{R}\vee\mathcal{S})^{\perp\perp}$. for every pair $(\mathcal{R},\mathcal{S})$ in $\{\mathcal{N},\mathcal{N}^{c},\mathcal{M},\mathcal{M}^{c}\}$. In this case, we write $p\sim q$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$, $\mathcal{D}$ be two abstract strict UMTCs and $\mathcal{M}$, $\mathcal{N}$ two von Neumann factors. Two braided actions $G_{1}:\mathcal{C}\hookrightarrow\operatorname{End}(\mathcal{M})$ and $G_{2}:\mathcal{D}\hookrightarrow\operatorname{End}(\mathcal{N})$ will be called isomorphic if there is a spatial isomorphism $\operatorname{Ad}_{U}:\mathcal{M}\rightarrow\mathcal{N}$ implementing a strict tensor isomorphism between the respective images which is also braided. Equivalently, the unique strict tensor isomorphism $F_{U}:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ which makes the following diagram commute $\begin{array}[]{ccr}\hskip 8.535827pt\mathcal{C}&\stackrel{{\scriptstyle G_{1}% }}{{\lhook\joinrel\relbar\joinrel\rightarrow}}&\operatorname{End}(\mathcal{M})% \\ \scriptstyle{F_{U}}\Big{\downarrow}&&\Big{\downarrow}\scriptstyle{% \operatorname{Ad}_{U}}\\ \hskip 8.535827pt\mathcal{D}&\stackrel{{\scriptstyle G_{2}}}{{\lhook\joinrel% \relbar\joinrel\rightarrow}}&\operatorname{End}(\mathcal{N})\end{array}$ is in addition a UBTC isomorphism.
Definition 2.4. A local conformal net on the line $\{\mathcal{A}\}$, as in Definition 2.1, is called completely rational if the following conditions are satisfied. (a) Haag duality on $\mathbb{R}$: $\mathcal{A}(I^{\prime})^{\prime}=\mathcal{A}(I)$ for all $I\in\mathcal{I}$. (b) Split property: for every $I,J\in\mathcal{I}$, $I\Subset J$ there exists a type $I$ factor $\mathcal{F}$ such that $\mathcal{A}(I)\subset\mathcal{F}\subset\mathcal{A}(J)$. (c) Finite index two-interval subfactor: $\mathcal{A}(I_{1}\cup I_{2})\subset\mathcal{A}(I)^{\prime}\cap\mathcal{A}(J)$ has finite Jones index, where $I,J\in\mathcal{I}$, $I\Subset J$ and $I^{\prime}\cap J=I_{1}\cup I_{2}$ for $I_{1},I_{2}\in\mathcal{I}$. With conformal covariance, see [GLW98], condition (a) is equivalent to (a)${}^{\prime}$ Strong additivity: $\mathcal{A}(I_{1}\cup I_{2})=\mathcal{A}(I)$ where $I\in\mathcal{I}$, $p\in I$ and $\{p\}^{\prime}\cap I=I\smallsetminus\{p\}=I_{1}\cup I_{2}$ for $I_{1},I_{2}\in\mathcal{I}$.
